// Cross-cutting middlewares declared in the `shared` package so
// every service in the project references the same set via
// `@middlewares(shared.<Name>)`. Middleware names are GLOBALLY
// unique across the project — the project-level resolver enforces
// uniqueness at semantic time so two packages cannot accidentally
// claim the same name.
//
// The interesting axis here is the THREE FORMS of middleware
// declaration:
//
//   - `middleware Name` — bare, no parameters. AuthRequired is the
//     canonical example: behaviour is fixed, no caller-supplied
//     knobs.
//   - `middleware Name(p: T = default, ...)` — parametric, with
//     compile-time defaults baked into the contract. RateLimit
//     declares its steady-state rate and burst allowance here so
//     callers see the policy without reading the impl.
//   - `middleware Name(p: int = 500ms)` — parametric with an INT
//     parameter taking a DURATION-LITERAL default. The semantic
//     analyser accepts `*ast.DurationLit` AND `*ast.IntLit` for
//     decorator slots typed `ArgDuration`, but middleware param
//     TYPES are validated against [BuiltinTypes] only — `duration`
//     as a spelling is rejected with
//     `unknown type "duration" (no built-in primitive ...)`.
//     The least-bad workaround: declare the param as `int` and let
//     the duration literal land in the default slot. The bug is
//     recorded in the report — there is no DSL-level path that
//     types the field as a Go time.Duration.
package shared

// AuthRequired enforces a Bearer token on every request flowing
// through it. The canonical no-arg middleware: behaviour is fixed,
// configuration (token lifetime, issuer, audience) lives in
// svccontext / config, not in the DSL contract.
middleware AuthRequired

// RateLimit applies a token-bucket per remote IP. `rps` is the
// steady-state refill rate (requests per second); `burst` is the
// bucket size that absorbs short spikes. Defaults match the
// project's standard "polite client" envelope — services that need
// a tighter or looser policy override the args at the
// `@middlewares(RateLimit(rps: 10, burst: 20))` call site.
middleware RateLimit(rps: int = 100, burst: int = 200)

// Timing emits a structured warn-log entry whenever a handler
// exceeds `threshold`. The default literal lands as
// `*ast.DurationLit` in the AST, so codegen still sees the
// "500ms" spelling — the param type is `int` only because the
// semantic checker rejects `duration` as a type spelling. See the
// package header for the rationale.
middleware Timing(threshold: int = 500ms)
